postcontent: Mossberg MMR Tactical Ar-15 "assault rifle" model #65014 new in box with paperwork, lock, and (1) 30 round aluminum magazines. This rifle features black phosphate/anodized aluminum finishes, a Stark SE-1 pistol grip with battery compartment, a 6 position adjustable stock by UTI, a Picatinny quad-rail forearm and top rail, rail mounted front/rear adjustable sights, and a stock sling mount. The free float rails are designed to fit all the tactical gear that you can carry. Unlike many ARs, this is a standard feature which you won't end up spending more to upgrade the rail set-ups. It has an efficient autoloading direct-impingement gas system for ejection of spent cartridges and auto reloading. No forward assist is necessary for a rifle this smooth. It does have a dust cover, a large trigger hole, and nice charging handle. The blued barrel is 16.25", rifled for 1 in 9" and ends with the muzzle-flash suppressor. The receiver, magazine release, and charging handle are all well designed to make use and maintenance reliable and easy. The upper and lower separate easily with two pins for service and cleaning. The receiver accepts 5.56 Nato ammunition as well as .223 Remington brass or steel casings. It has a 31 round capacity and is a real front-runner in the AR style market. Colt also makes a good quad rail set-up like this, but is generally much more costly. Mossberg redefined affordable with .223s and the .22lr. They have been around over 90 years. They must be doing something right. Mossberg offers their one year manu. warranty on this product. I have additional 30 round factory Mossberg magazines for sale

postcontent:
I have here a Ruger 44 Mag Carbine with a beautiful stock.  I contacted Ruger and they told me based on the serial number that the gun was made in 1980 and came with an 18 1/2 inch barrel and a Walnut Stock. 

The only blemishes I found on the gun was where the bullets are entered into the tub, which unless it is brand new I have never seen one without a little bluing missing there.

The other is on the shiny metal where the charging handle goes into the slide assembly, look at pic and you will see a small about 3/8" circular blemish on the metal by the cocking handle.  I believe a dremel and some polishing would take this out.

A family member of mine bought this Carbine off Armslist about 6 months ago for $750 as it is.  I did just put Weaver scope bases on the gun.  He decided he does not want to hunt and gave me the rifle.  I already have the same rifle though, so I don't need a second one.

I stripped the rifle down and gave it a thorough cleaning and lubed it with oil and Frog Lube.  

I have had 2 surgeries in the last 6 months and my family member never goes to the range, so neither of us has even fired the rifle.
